lementor-element-populated\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-a21d566 elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading\" data-id=\"a21d566\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"heading.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default\">The Natural World<\/h3>\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-7ef03331 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor\" data-id=\"7ef03331\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"text-editor.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p><strong>Extinctions are up to 1000 times the normal rate, as a result of human activity<\/strong>. In the last 50 years, the populations of all mammals, birds, reptiles and fish have fallen by an average of 60%.<\/p><p>Insects are becoming extinct eight times faster than mammals, birds and reptiles. They could vanish within a century, with catastrophic consequences for the planet\u2019s ecosystems and for human survival.<\/p><p>Among the culprits are: habitat loss due to agriculture and climate change; hunting and fishing; pollution and pesticides.<\/p>\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/section>\n\t\t\t\t<section class=\"elementor-section elementor-top-section elementor-element elementor-element-949fcdc elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default\" data-id=\"949fcdc\" data-element_type=\"section\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-4cdcfa5d\" data-id=\"4cdcfa5d\" data-element_type=\"column\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-wrap elementor-element-populated\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-elem